node: close | Phinneas
  *(Doddering Phinneas slumps back over his cup, declaiming the bottom of the abyss to a room that laughs — the philosopher who followed a thought one step too far and has drunk for eleven years to blur its edge — and whether you walked him down to the floor of it and stood there with him, or let him drown the thread again, you carry away the quiet rescue hidden in the saga's argument: that the terror of a silent, meaning-less universe is not the silence itself but *facing it alone*, and that the same cold floor which breaks the solitary thinker becomes, with one other soul standing on it, not a pit of despair but a foundation to build meaning *on, by hand.*)*

# ─── 94 ─── Roen's Old Fence — raised the companion Roen, holds the secret that could unmake him ───
conversation: npc.lantern.fence | Old Sabira, the Fence
node: 0 | Old Sabira
  *(In a curtained nook behind the Low Lantern's bar, an old woman appraises a brooch through a jeweler's loupe with hands that have handled ten thousand stolen things. She does not look up, but she knows you're there, and she knows — somehow — that you keep company with someone she cares about.)* You travel with Roen. *(she sets the brooch down.)* Don't bother denying it. I can *smell* my own on a person — Roen's *careful*, *watches the exits*, *stands* a certain way. You've picked up the *posture*, a little. Spend enough time with my *girl* and you *would.* *(she finally looks up, eyes sharp as the loupe.)* I'm Sabira. I *fence* — stolen goods in, clean coin out, no questions, fair rates. *(quietly.)* And I *raised* that one. So before you say *anything* — tell me. Is *Roen* well? *Truly* well? Because *I'm* the one person *alive* who'd *know* if you *lied.*
  enter: SET npc.sabira_met
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Old Sabira
  *(She sets the loupe aside, and the hard fence softens, fractionally, into something maternal and worried.)* I took Roen in off the *street.* *Small.* *Starving.* *Light-fingered* even *then* — lifted my *own* purse, which is how we *met*, and I was so *impressed* a *child* got it *off me* that I *kept* the *child* instead of the *purse.* *(a thin smile.)* Taught Roen *everything.* Locks. Marks. How to *read* a room, *vanish* from one, *survive* in the *cracks* of a *city* that *wants* the *poor* *dead.* *(her smile fades.)* And I taught *too* well, maybe. Because there's a *thing* in Roen's *past* — a *thing* that *happened*, back when Roen was *young* and *desperate* and *following* my *teaching* a *little* too *faithfully* — a *thing* I *helped* *cover*, a *thing* that, if it *came out*, would *unmake* everything Roen's *built* since. *(she meets your eyes, and the fence is gone, only the worried parent remains.)* I *carry* it. The *secret.* The *one* that could *destroy* my *girl.* I've carried it for *years*, *alone*, and I'll carry it to my *grave* — *but.* *(her voice tightens.)* You're *traveling* into *danger* with Roen. Toward a *Wall* that *reads* people's *pasts*, I *hear.* And I find myself *afraid*, old fence that I am, that the *thing I've buried* will get *dug up* out *there*, far from where I can *bury* it again — and that *Roen* will face it *alone*, with *no one* who *knows* the *whole* of it standing *near.* *(quietly.)* So. *Two* questions, traveler. Is Roen *well.* And — if the *buried* thing *surfaces* — can I *trust* you to stand by my girl when it *does?*
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You didn't bury Roen's secret to protect Roen. You buried it to protect *yourself* — from the part you played in it. You taught 'too faithfully,' you said. Whatever Roen did desperate and young, *you* set it in motion. The secret isn't Roen's shame you're keeping. It's *yours.*" -> yours ?? guard
  * "Roen is well — and stronger than you fear. You raised someone who survives. But a secret kept *for* someone, never *told* them, isn't protection — it's a cage with a kind warden. Maybe what Roen needs isn't the secret buried deeper. It's *you*, telling it, so it stops owning you both." -> tell
  * "I'll stand by Roen — you have my word. But you should know what I've learned on this road: the Wall doesn't destroy people by *exposing* their pasts. It destroys them by making them believe their worst act is their *whole name.* If Roen's buried thing surfaces, the danger isn't the truth. It's the shame." -> shame | fx SET sq.roen_secret
  * "What did Roen *do*, Sabira? You don't have to tell me the whole of it — but I'm walking toward the danger with your girl, and I'd rather know the shape of the ghost than meet it blind in the dark." -> what | fx appr.roen +2
node: yours | Old Sabira
  *(The loupe-sharp eyes flinch, and the old fence sits back as though you've reached across the table and turned a card she'd kept face-down for years.)* ...Mine. *(quietly.)* You've a *cruel* eye, traveler. *Cruel* and *true*, which is *worse.* *(she folds her weathered hands.)* Yes. *(barely above a whisper.)* The *thing* Roen *did* — the *desperate*, *young*, *terrible* thing — Roen did it because *I* sent the child to do a job that was *too big*, *too dangerous*, for *coin* *I* wanted, and it *went wrong*, the way I *should* have *known* it might, and someone — *(her voice catches)* — someone *died*, who *needn't* have, and *Roen*, *fourteen* and *terrified*, did what a *cornered* child *does*, and I — *I* *cleaned* it up. *Buried* it. *Told* Roen it was *handled*, *forgotten*, *gone.* *(she meets your eyes.)* And I've *let* my *girl* carry the *guilt* of it *alone* for *years* — *let* Roen believe it was *Roen's* *crime*, *Roen's* *failing* — when the *truth* is *I* *sent* a *child* into a *grown* man's *danger* for *my* *profit*, and the *blood* is *mine*, the *plan* was *mine*, the *fault* is *mine.* *(her hands tremble.)* I didn't *bury* the secret to *protect* Roen. I buried it to keep my *girl* from ever *knowing* that the *person* who *saved* her off the *street*, who she *loves* like a *mother*, is *also* the *person* who *damned* her with a *job* no *child* should've been *given.* *(quietly, undone.)* The secret I've been *guarding* isn't *Roen's* shame. It's that *Roen's* shame was *always* *mine.* And I let the *child* carry *my* sin so I could *keep* being *loved.* *(she looks at you.)* That's the *thing* in the *dark*, traveler. Not what *Roen* did. What *I* did *to* *Roen.*
  enter: SET npc.sabira_yours, SET sq.roen_secret, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.roen +5
  auto: close
node: tell | Old Sabira
  *(She is quiet a long moment, the jeweler's loupe turning over and over in her fingers.)* A cage with a kind warden. *(softly.)* ...You sound like someone who's *seen* a *Wall* do *exactly* that. *(she sets the loupe down.)* I've told myself, *years* now, that *keeping* the secret *from* Roen was the *kindest* thing — that *knowing* would only *hurt*, that some *truths* are *better* *buried.* *(her voice tightens.)* But you're right that I've never *asked* whether *Roen* would *rather* *carry* the *truth* than be *protected* from it. I *decided.* *For* my girl. The way I *decided* about the *job*, all those years ago. *(she winces.)* I keep *deciding* what *Roen* can *bear*, and I keep *getting* it *wrong*, because I'm *deciding* out of *my* *fear*, not *Roen's* *strength.* *(she meets your eyes.)* And a secret I keep *for* Roen but never *tell* Roen — it doesn't *protect* my girl. It just means there's a *locked room* between us, *forever*, that *I* hold the *only* key to, and Roen can *feel* the *locked door* even if not what's *behind* it, and *that* — that *distance*, that *thing-we-don't-speak-of* — is its *own* kind of *wall.* *(quietly.)* Maybe the *bravest* thing left to an old fence is to *unlock* the door. *Tell* Roen the *whole* of it — *my* fault, *my* plan, *my* sin dressed as the *child's* — and let *Roen* *decide* what to *do* with a *mother* who *damned* and *saved* in the *same* hand. *(her voice shakes.)* It might *cost* me Roen's *love.* But *love* built on a *locked* room was *never* the *whole* thing anyway. *Help* me tell it, traveler. I've *buried* it so *long* I've forgotten how to *dig* *up* instead of *down.*
  enter: SET npc.sabira_tell, SET sq.roen_secret, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.roen +5
  auto: close
node: shame | Old Sabira
  *(She goes very still, and the loupe stops in her hand, and something in the old fence's face cracks open at the word.)* The danger isn't the truth. It's the *shame.* *(quietly.)* ...Say that *again*, traveler. *Slowly.* I want to *hold* it. *(you say it again: the Wall destroys people not by exposing their worst act, but by making them believe it's their whole name.)* *(she closes her eyes.)* That's — that's *exactly* what's *happened* to my girl, isn't it. *(her voice roughens.)* Roen *doesn't* even need the *Wall* to *do* it. Roen's been doing it to *Roen* for *years* — taking that *one* terrible *night* and letting it *become* the *whole* *story*, the *secret* *name*, the *thing-I-really-am-under-the-careful-rogue.* *(she opens her eyes, fierce now.)* And I *helped.* By *burying* it, by *never* speaking it, I made it a *thing-too-shameful-to-name* — which is *exactly* how you make a *single* act into a *whole* *identity*: you *wrap* it in *silence* until the *silence* *teaches* the person it's *unspeakable*, *unforgivable*, *who-they-are.* *(she grips your arm.)* Then the *medicine* isn't *deeper* burial. It's the *opposite.* It's *saying* the thing *out loud*, *plainly*, in *daylight* — *"Roen, you did a terrible thing at fourteen, cornered and desperate, and it is* one thing you did, *not the* whole *of who you are"* — and *robbing* it of the *shame-power* that *silence* gave it. *(quietly, resolved.)* You've told me how the *Wall* *wins*, traveler. *Shame*, *fed* by *silence*, *grown* into a *name.* Then I know how to *fight* it for my *girl*: *break the silence*, *name the act*, *refuse the shame.* *Before* the *Wall* — or *Roen's* *own* *heart* — *finishes* the *job* I *started* with my *burying.*
  enter: SET npc.sabira_shame, SET sq.roen_secret, SET act5.shame_feeds_the_wall, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.roen +4
  auto: close
node: what | Old Sabira
  *(She studies you a long moment, weighing how much of the ghost to show, then gives you its shape — not its whole face, but enough.)* The shape of it. *(quietly.)* All right. You're owed *that* much, walking into the *dark* with my girl. *(she lowers her voice.)* When Roen was *fourteen*, there was a *job.* A *house* in the *Upper City.* Meant to be *empty.* It *wasn't.* *(her jaw tightens.)* There was a *struggle, in the dark — Roen, *small* and *terrified*, and a *man*, *grown*, who *caught* the *child* and *would* not *let go*, and *meant*, I think, *real* harm — and in the *scramble*, the *man* *fell.* *Wrong.* *Hit* his *head.* And he *didn't* get up. *(she meets your eyes.)* It *wasn't* murder. A *court* would call it *barely* even Roen's *fault* — a *cornered* child, a *grown* aggressor, a *terrible* accident in the *dark.* *(her voice hardens.)* But Roen doesn't *carry* it as an *accident.* Roen carries it as *"I killed a man at fourteen."* Flat. *Whole.* *Damning.* *(quietly.)* And there's *more* — there's the *part* about *who* the man *was*, and *why* the house *wasn't* empty, and the *part* that's *mine* to *answer* for — but *that's* the *shape* of the *ghost*, traveler. A *dead* man, a *dark* room, a *frightened* child who's spent *years* calling an *accident* a *murder*, and an *old* fence who *knows* it *wasn't* and has *never* found the *words* to *convince* the *one* person who *needs* to *believe* it. *(she meets your eyes.)* *Stand* near my girl when it *surfaces.* And if you can — *help* Roen hear what *I* never could *make* heard: *it was not murder, and it was not your whole name, and you were a* child.*
  enter: SET npc.sabira_what, SET sq.roen_secret, appr.roen +3
  auto: close
node: guard | Old Sabira
  *(The maternal worry hardens back into the wary fence, and she picks the loupe up again, shielding herself behind the trade.)* You ask a *great* many *questions* for someone who only *travels* with Roen. *(coolly.)* My girl's *secrets* are *Roen's* to *give*, not *mine* to *spill* to a *sharp-eyed* stranger in a *back* room, *however* kind your *face.* *(she returns to the brooch.)* I asked you *two* things: is Roen *well*, and will you *stand* by Roen. *Answer* *those*, and we're *square.* The *rest* — the *buried* thing, the *shape* of the *ghost* — *stays* buried, where I *put* it, where it's *safe.* *(she peers through the loupe.)* I've kept it *years*, traveler. I'll not *un-keep* it for *curiosity*, even *kind* curiosity. *Look* after my girl. That's *all* I *need* from *you.* The *digging* — if there's *digging* to be *done* — that's *mine*, and *Roen's*, and *no one* else's. *(and she bends back over the stolen brooch, the old fence sealing the vault, guarding her girl's secret and her own with the same practiced, loving wariness.)*
  auto: close
node: close | Old Sabira
  *(Old Sabira bends back over her loupe and her stolen brooch in the curtained nook behind the bar — the fence who raised the companion Roen off the street and has buried, for years, the secret that could unmake them both — and whether you drew out that the buried shame was always hers to carry or left the vault sealed, you carry away one more turn of the saga's central truth: that a single terrible act, wrapped long enough in protective silence, curdles into a whole identity — and that the cure the Wall most fears is the same one an old fence must find the courage for: to name the act in daylight, refuse it the power of shame, and tell the one you love *that was a thing you did, not the whole of who you are.*)*
